#repost — There’s something exciting forming within Charlotte-Mecklenburg Schools. The CMS Male Empowerment Network (M.E.N.) is a new mentoring program focused on promoting the importance of fathers and positive male role models in schools. This will be piloted in 14 Title I Schools in the area.

The program focuses on four pillars: attendance and academic success; restorative practices; the power of presence; and life after high school (both college and career). Led by CMS Family Engagement Specialist Harold C. Dixon, each pillar of the program will be led by a network of community organizations and volunteers, including @therealfredshropshire of WCNC-TV, @mbkcltmeck, Be There Dad, @projectbolt2018, @allprodad, and the Renaissance West Community Initiative (@rwciimpact).

This is an incredible opportunity for the men in our area to help empower the children in our community and equip them with the tools they need to be successful. As the title of the article suggests (linked in our bio), Superman ain’t comin’, but the men are!

#PrideMagazine #CMSMaleEmpowermentNetwork #CMSMEN #CharlotteSchools #BeThereDad #mentor #mentorship #makeadifference #seethedifference #wcnc #therealfredshropshire

It’s a blessing to be able to serve; thank you for inviting me. 💜🙏🏾

#repost • @wcnctv TO THOSE WHO HAVE SERVED: WCNC Charlotte is exposing a government failure that's leaving veterans waiting, at length, for decisions about their disability benefits.

A half million dollars hangs in the balance for one veteran we spoke to. We know of up to 200,000 other veterans waiting for decisions about their claims.

In the meantime, we're pushing for solutions and helping connect veterans to lawmakers, attorneys and other resources that can help.

@nateinvestigates and @therealfredshropshire are hosting a virtual town hall Thursday at 8 p.m. where you can get real-time answers from our panel of experts about your benefits as a #veteran or your loved one's benefits. 

You can ask your questions live during the event or you can comment below and we'll ask them during the event. #linkinbio for more details about the investigation and how you can attend the virtual town hall.

LIFE UPDATE:

I'm thrilled to share I’ve accepted a role as a weekday anchor/reporter at NBC10, the NBCU station in Philadelphia. 🔔🇺🇸🏙️ 
 
While I’m excited to take this next step in my journey, I must say this wasn’t an easy choice for my family. Countless prayers and months of reflection went into this decision. We have so much love and gratitude for our church (which will remain the same), friends, WCNC colleagues and viewers who have supported us over the years.
 
I'll have plenty more to say about all of this and many people to thank personally over the next couple of months since I’ll be here through mid May, so stay tuned.
 
But I'll leave you with this: I don't ever expect to completely say goodbye to Charlotte because by now you should all know how much I deeply care about this community. ❤️👑🙏🏾

#therealfredshropshire

I’ll always have the best views in Philly.

#newbeginnings #withmyfavoriteperson #cityviews #therealfredshropshire

The past 8 years have been exceptionally challenging for me, personally.

Earlier in that journey … at a time when it would’ve been easy to isolate, not be accountable or even worse — God blessed me with an impressive men’s group that lead to some incredible friendships.

As I close this chapter and enter into a new season I’m thankful for y’all.

It’s been good to see most of you recently.

I see y’all, I love y’all and I’m proud of y’all.

As she prepares to take office in the new year, democratic Mayor-elect Cherelle Parker will name Kevin Bethel as Philadelphia's new police commissioner after outgoing commissioner Danielle Outlaw resigned in September, law enforcement sources confirmed with NBC10.⁠
⁠
Parker is expected to make the announcement during a press conference Wednesday at 10 a.m. at City Hall. ⁠
⁠
Bethel, 60, is currently the Chief Safety Officer for the School District of Philadelphia, a position he's held since 2019. ⁠
⁠
